column168: This container PAFX500849-7/WB2116639, was released to Horizon on 5/31/08 and loaded on the TW720N in Tacoma/Wa for transit to Anchorage. On a random inspection  of this container in Anchorage, it was found that the HAZ declaration failed to have the battery acid declared, UN2796/Class 3. An update was made and the shipper notified for the shipment to continue.
column169: Shipper must review all shipments for material loaded to ensure the paperwork properly reflects all hazmat materialsloade. This needs to be done prior to pick-up at their facility, so that the trucker and the carrier have accurate paperwork. This must especialy be done when they are shipping new vehicles and the battery acid is shipped with the vehicle, but in their original bottled containers.

column168: Shipper released this container, HRZU430057-8/WB2104300, on 5/31/08 for pick-up and it was loaded to the TW720N in Tacoma,Wa for transit to Anchorage. After discharge in Anchorage, and during a random inspection it was found that the shipper failed to include UN1030/Class 2.1 on their hazmat declaration. Shipper was advised and updates were made for shipment to continue.
column169: Shipper must review the load against the hazmat paperwork to make sure all hazardous material are included. This must be accomplished prior to having it picked-up at their facility, so the trucker and carrier are provided with accurate paperwork.

column168: On June 2nd 2008 at approximately 0930 a Univar employee noticed that liquid was leaking from the top 2" bung of a Hazardous Waste drum. It was determined that the bung was loose.  The bung was tightened and the spilled material, approximately 12 ounces, was cleaned up and will be disposed of according to State and Federal regulations.
column169: The customer has been contacted by the Univar Sales representative who then informed the customer that all bungs must be verified and closed to the required torque requirements.   In addition, all Univar drivers will check to verify that all bungs are tight before picking up product from a customer.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE VEOLIA 10-DAY INTRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, A DRUM PREVIOUSLY LOADED AT THE REAR OF AN OUTBOUND TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS QUICKLY PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FROM LEAKING OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. TRAINED VEOLIA EMPLOYEES WERE QUICK TO RESPOND AND PROPERLY OVERPACKED THE DRUM INTO A 301H2 DF. THE SMALL SPILL CONSISTING OF APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF A FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPEEDY-DRI AND PLACED INTO A SPILL CONTAINER WHICH WAS PROPERLY LABELED AND PLACED IN THE SAT ACCUMULATION AREA ONSITE AT THE FACILITY. THE SPILLED MATERIAL DID NOT LEAVE THE REAR OF THE TRUCK AND DID NOT LEAK ONTO SEALED PAVED ASPHALT OF THE PARKING LOT. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT DURING LOADING, THE DRUM MAY HAVE BEEN PLACED UP AGAINST A NEARBY PALLET WHICH COULD HAVE CAUSED THE PIN-SIZED HOLE APX 1-2 INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER.
column169: THE ON-SITE FACILITY SUPERVISOR LATER MET WITH HIS EMPLOYEES ON THE AFTERNOON OF THE SPILL TO REVIEW PROPER LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND DRUM HANDLING. THE CAUSE OF THE HOLE IS UNKNOWN BUT THE DRUM WAS NOT LEAKING WHEN IT ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY, BUT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ONCE PLACED ONTO THE TRAILER.

column168: We were notified by a passing motorist that an odor was coming from our cargo tank so our driver stopped, and found there was a small spill underneath the spill tubes coming down from the dome lid.  A DOT officer instructed our driver to move to an isolated area where he performed a inspection of the unit.  I dispatched a man to go inspect the unit to check the wash out caps as well as the dome lid to make sure they all were secured.       A small part of the dome gasket around the dome lid that is attached to the lid in this case was hanging  down into the trailer creating a void around the dome lid.  The seals were broken and the gasket was repaired then the trailer was returned to the ETC terminal to have an external wash to eliminate any lingering odor.    Our driver sprayed a neutralizer on the spilled acrylate to neutralize the odor and it was absorbed with floor dry and swept up to the satisfaction of the police officer.
column169: Plant personnel need to be reminded and/or educated that you should never allow a dome lid to free fall or slam it shut as it tends to cause the dome gasket to become loose or fall from its track.  In some cases, the gasket has been found inside the cargo tank.
column198: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.

column168: We prepared to deliver the load at the consignee but when the internal and external valves were opened, product started leaking out of the side of the discharge outlet leg where it had once been welded.  The load was transferred into another cargo tank and was subsequently delivered at a later date.      The outlet leg on the initial trailer has been replaced while the original outlet leg was thrown into the junk pile after it was cleaned.      There was a dry disconnect fitting on the end of the faulty outleg leg that placed too much stress on it causing the weld to crack open.  It appears that it may have been welded on more than one occasion in the past.
column169: Trailers that have to be equipped with dry disconnect fittings will be selected carefully to make sure there are no apparent defects that the weight of this fitting may aggravate.  Once a discharge outlet leg develops a leak in the sidewall of the piping, we will replace the piping with a new one.
column198: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.

column168: On 06/05/2008 at 18:20, personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard discovered UTLX 210983, a loaded tank car of denatured alcohol, leaking from top valve area. The car was isolated and CHEMTREC, Illinois EMA and Riverdale, IL 911 were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2008-06-05-00260). Eagle Construction, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line ball valve open and the valve plug less than tool tight. The vapor valve plug was also less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened both plugs, closed the liquid valve fully and decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  199  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route between the shipper’s location and the intended waste management facility.  During a routine stop at Clean Harbor’s Chicago, IL location, it was discovered that approximately 3 gallons of material had escaped from the bottom of one of the containers on the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately activated the internal emergency response plan and initiated the clean-up activities.  Using appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel entered the trailer and discovered that a 55 gallon container was punctured by a nail that was protruding from the pallet it was loaded on.  Facility personnel placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum and absorbed all free liquids with a suitable absorbent material.  The clean-up debris was placed into the salvage drum and it along with the damaged container was placed back on the trailer for disposal at the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent an occurrence, the driver has been reinstructed to inspect not only the floor of the van trailer but the loading devices used to consolidate and move freight onto and off of his truck.  All pallets must be inspected and those found to be broken or found to have nails protruding from the slats are to be repaired or removed from the vehicle.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched to a shipper’s location to pick-up a non-DOT specification sift proof bulk bin in order to transport it to a hazardous waste disposal facility for processing.  At the time of the pick-up, the container was inspected and no evidence of leaking was observed nor was there evidence of residual liquid in the container.  Approximately 5 miles away from the pick-up location, the driver noticed a small amount of material leaking from the side of the container.  The driver immediately moved his vehicle off the traveled portion of the roadway and inspected the container.  The driver identified a small crack had developed in the side of the container allowing a small amount of material to escape from the box. It is believed that residual liquid not visible at the time of pick-up separated from the solid material and was able to escape from the crack discovered by the driver. Once secured, the driver contacted his home dispatcher to report the incident.  Calls were immediately placed to the Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality and the Louisiana State Police.  Upon arrival at the scene, it was decided that a local emergency response contractor be contracted to place a temporary patch on the box and clean up the estimated 2 solid gallons of material that escaped onto the side of the truck and the roadway.  This was done and all clean-up debris was added to the container for continuing transportation.  Once the clean-up was complete and the box was patched, the clean-up contractor escorted the vehicle back to the shipper’s location where the load was transferred into an alternate container for continued transportation.
column169: Upon arrival at the shipper's location, the driver inspected the container and did not identify any evidence of material leaking or damage to the structural integity of the container.  The driver, however, has been re-instructed to insure that prior to accepting any container for transport that a comprehensive inspection is performed and to question any areas of a container whose structural integrity could be suspect.

column168: When trailer arrived at the unloading facility, dock worker noticed a solvent smell coming from the trailer.  No other obvious evidence of a spill.  When the unloader picked up the shipment in question, he did a further inspection of it at the back door of the trailer.   A crease was found in a box that contained 4 gallons of SEM Solve.  The box was opened, and it was discovered that one of the one gallon metal cans in the box had a crease across the width of the can and there was a half in split in the side of the can. It appeared that a skid of freight loaded adjacent to the hazardous material had contacted the box and caused the damage.  Approximately 3 quarts of product had leaked out and evaporated.   Shipment was recouped and forwarded for delivery.   Leaking can was held in hazardous materials bay and is awaiting disposal via environmental contractor.

column168: GATX 56550 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the top of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found the manway cover gasket missing allowing product to escape during movement.  The manway gasket was replaced stopping the release.    The car was noted by carrier personnel leaking from the top again on June 16, in Salisbury, NC.  Hepaco representatives responded and found the previously installed manway gasket had blown-out of position allowing product to escape during movement.    The gasket was realigned and the manway cover secured stopping the release.

column168: On June 6, 2008 at 17:40 CSX Transportation personnel observed tank car GATX 36071, Residue: Last Contained Methanol Solutions, dripping from its bottom outlet area. The leak was reported as 1 drop per every 2 seconds. CSX Transportation personnel notified the local 911 center (Lucas County, OH) who dispatched their personnel to the scene. The shipper, Perstorp, Incorporated, of Toledo, OH was notified by CSX Transportation and they also responded. Perstorp personnel reported the leak at the bottom outlet. Perstorp, Incorporated personnel stopped leak by tightening the bottom outlet cap.    NARRI:   5(4 + 3 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 70    Cause Code: 149
column169: No additional comments.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, one fiberboard box, containing four (4) one-liter plastic jugs was punctured by the forklift.  Approximately one-pint of free product was released and impacted another carton containing the same material.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. of Mount Arlington, New Jersey was dispatched to perform the cleanup.      Upon arrival, H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. performed an investigation, and determined that one, one-liter jug was damaged and that the remaining three jugs were impacted beyond recovery.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid.  The damaged carton with entire contents, and contaminated absorbent material were placed into one, 55-gallon recovery drum and one, 30-gallon recovery drum.  The contents of the impacted carton were cleaned, repackaged, and forwarded with the remainder of the shipment to the consignee.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.  No injuries or exposures were reported.

column168: June 20, 2008: CR Stoney Creek Yard, Trainer, PA: At approximately 7:00AM, Mechanical Car inspector noted a hissing originating from top of tank car UTLX 38128, residue last contained Petroleum Gases, Liquefied (Propane/Propylene).  He also noted a clear wave-like vapor from the side of the protective housing on top of the car.  This car was pulled from the shipper, Sunoco Inc., Marcus Hook, PA, by Stoney Creek crew YPSC33, on 6/19/08, at approximately 645pm.    Further inspection by Union Tank Car Inspector, Sunoco, and representatives of REACT Environmental (contracted by shipper, Sunoco) found the vapor valve closure plug not applied and same valve slightly opened.  Valve was secured and plug resecured tool tight, securing the leak.  Also noted one of the liquid valve closure plugs was not applied.  Resecured during this inspection.    During inspection of all other fittings inside the housing, found a very slight vapor leak originating from the area where the threaded pipe nipple for the Sample Line Valve threads into the pressure plate.  As car was in residue status, car will be returned to the Sunoco facility from where it originated, at which time the car will be depressurized and shopped for repair of the Sample Line.

There was no package failure and no release of product, in the traditional sense.  Two boxes of detonating cord (UN0289) fell out of the back of a pickup truck as it was traveling between Clarksburg, WV and Weston, WV. The boxes were contained within an enclosure in the covered bed of the vehicle, the tailgate acted as the fourth wall of the enclosure.  The tailgate opened in transit allowing the boxes to drop out of the vehicle.  Once the loss was discovered, the police and ATF in Clarksburg, WV became involved. A police report was filed in Clarksburg, WV and a loss report was filed with ATF's US Bomb Data Center. A nine person search team searched the entire route by foot and car on 6/17 and a four person search team (third party) searched the route on 6/18.      Both boxes were recovered by private citizens on 6/17 and 6/18; both still contained the product, no damage occurred to the packaging.
column169: Operating procedures have been improved to prevent the possibility of recurrence.  This includes the use of cargo stabilization bars which ratchet into place to securely stabilize the load, use of a tailgate net as a secondary securement device and a lock has been added to the tailgate which is to be locked each time the tailgate is closed.

column168: 6/23/08: Mack Yard, Detroit, MI: At appoximately 8:45AM, CR crew FD-06 switching cars in yard was notified by CR crew FD-08 that a tank car was noted leaking from the top on track #17.    Local supervision contacted consignee, PVS Technologies, Detroit, MI, who inspected the car, finding one of the four liquid eduction line closure flange securement bolt washers missing.  It appeared that during transportation during original loading of this car, without benefit of the washer, the securement nut for said bolt was tighted, whereby pinching the closure flange, prohibiting proper securement.    PVS Tech. personnel replaced all four liquid eduction line closure flange securement bolt washers and nuts/bolts, and resecured the car.  PVS Tech. also decontaminated and cleaned area on car and ground where product had spilled, for proper disposal at later date.  Car okay to move to destination as intended.

column168: Univar driver picked up some waste at Honeywell Engines on Friday June 13, 2008.  Part of this pick up was two tri-wall cubic yard boxes containing Metal Hydroxide Sludge, Class 9 Misc. (Tri-wall is a large cubic yard cardboard box with a heavy duty black plastic bag inside the box.  The box is nailed to a wooden pallet and the bag, which is considered the inner packing, will hold the waste solids.)  This particular waste was scheduled to ship out of Univar 10 day waste storage on Friday June 20, 2008, going to US Ecology Beatty in Beatty, NV.  Univar material handler, Jeff Fitzgerald, was preparing a truckload of waste for an outbound shipment.  Jeff, using a forklift, lifted the tri-wall and Lead Material Handler, Mike Flores, saw some liquid leaking from the box as he lifted it.  The box was set onto a another containment pallet for further observation.  The box was leaking liquid out of two corners and there was approximately 2-3 ounces of liquid at most.  The liquid that leaked out was tested for ph and was determined to be neutral (PH of seven).   After a few phone calls B.O.S., Greg Walker, decided to called third party company (CTI) to repack the leaking container.    Tri-wall was repackaged; all contents were placed in a new tri-wall and labels were affixed, box sealed and prepped for shipment.
column169: Not sure that any changes in the process would have eliminated this container from leaking.  Since it was the inner packaging that leaked it was not officially determined how or where it failed.  The inner packaging (plastic bag) needs to be inspected for defects and or holes prior to placing the bag into the fiberboard outer packaging. Any impacts to the inner packaging could compromise the integrity of the entire packaging.

Shipper representatives, Petro-Chem, responded and found 2 leaking drums near the front of the container.    1 drum was leaking from the bottom due to being punctured by a screw protruding from the floor of the container.  1 drum was leaking from the botton edge seam due to abrasion from movement of the drum during transit.  Movement of the drums was due to inadequate blocking and bracing allowing the drums to shift during transportation.      Both leaking drums were removed and overpacked to prevent further loss of product.  The entire shipment was transferred to another container for further transportation to destination.  The original container was decontaminated and repaired.

column169: TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND OR CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MW PALLETS, PLYWI AND OR DUNNAGE. AVOID LOADING HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF TOTES, TO PREVENT PRESSURE BUILD-UP, RESULTING IN THE LID OR CAP TO POP OFF. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK WITH CUSHIONS AND PIECES OF DUNNAGE TO ENSURE A NAIL OR SHARP OBJECT DOES NOT PUNCTURED THE TOTE. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLIN OF CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE AND THAT PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. column168: On June 17th, 2008 at approximately 10:00, Personnel discovered an odor in the CSXT Lafayette, IN yard.  A residue Anhydrous Ammonia Car ,UTLX 950252, was noted to have a strong odor of ammonia in the immediate vicinity of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, local, state and/or federal authorities were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2208-06-17-00072). A response contractor was dispatched and noted that the odor was coming from a small leak located between the pressure plate and man-way nozzle.  Bolts 6 through 12 were not secured enough to prevent vapor release from excursion area.  Contractor personnel utilized a large impact wrench and secured the car.  The lessee of the car was notified and has acquired a request for special move permit from the FRA (Approval number is 08060201).   The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  212  NARRI:  2 (4+9+0) x (2+0) = 52

column168: The trailer arrived at our Lubbock, TX facility and it was noticed that liquid was dripping from the trailer. This trailer was a full load of 6 totes and 12 drums with various chemicals including hazardous materials and non-regulated materials. It appears the bottom of 1 tote of a hazardous material   collapsed and the pressure blew center cap off (bung) of the tote. This allowed the liquid to spray upwards onto the roof, walls and floor of trailer. A hazmat team was called and responded to the terminal. They transferred the product out of the tote to drums and cleaned and neutralized the traile  r and empty tote.
column169: The condition of the metal cage around the plastic tote had certainly failed prior to arrival at our Lubbock terminal. The pictures indicate rust and fatigue of the metal structure surrounding the plastic tote. The rust and fatigue was particularly bad on one bottom corner of the metal structure. Wh  en it collapsed, it allowed the inner plastic tote to shift downwards in the metal cage putting pressure onto the plastic tote. This is most likely what caused the bung to blow out of the larger cap allowing the liquid to spray upwards out of the tote. The condition of the packages should be inspect  ed prior to placing them into transportation.

column168: June 30, 2008: Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ: At approximately 12:30PM, while performing an outbound train inspection train NS39G on Track 15 Support, Conrail Car Inspectors noted tank car GATX 6614, load Sulfuric Acid, Spent, leaking from one side, originating from the top.  It was reported to be a slow steady stream.      Further inspection by CR Risk Mgmt. Dept. A. Richter and REACT (environmental emergency response contractor) R. Gould, found the liquid eduction pipe closure cap less than hand tight, allowing product to exit the car, only leaking down the left side of the car (although staining on right side indicated a former leak as well).  A poly trough was placed under the left side of the car to capture/contain spilled material.  The cap was tightened and leak secured; and cars' vapor pressure slowly vented down.  Cap secured tool tight.  Phone conversations with DuPont emergency response personnel confirmed closure cap-to-pipe connection was a metal to metal seat and did not require a gasket or o-ring.  Sides of car were wiped down with chemical absorbant pads.      Area underneath car was treated with lime to neutralize.  Car moved to Pavonia Yard Car Shop for better access to clean/decon car on Tuesday, 7/1/08, and forward car to original destination.  Estimated 1 gallon of product loss at time of incident.  Representatives of NJ DEP and Camden Count Health, Environmental and Hazmat also on scene, as well as Camden City Fire Department Shift officer.    Also noted; placards displayed on the car at time of inspection noted to bear the identification numbers "1830", conflicting with the identification number displayed on the movement documents "1832".  Shipper, DuPont, Deepwater, NJ, supplied new placards with the correct identification number "1832" to be applied at the car shop, prior to offering the car back into transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On June 30, 2008 at 07:30 personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX 130433, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid Solution, leaking a slight vapor (wisp) cloud from the top area of the car as it was being humped. The car was isolated and shipper, local, state and/or federal agencies were notified (CHEMTREC Report- #2008-06-30-00021). Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the site along with the area Hazardous Materials Officer from CSXT. Residue material was noted on top of car, near appurtenances and fittings, along with some residue near the ladder wells.  Upon further investigation it was noted that the liquid induction line four-bolt cap had one bolt that was less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened the bolt and inspected all other bolts and the rupture disk for integrity.  The top and sides of the car were decontaminated. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 242  NARRI:  2 (4+5+0) x (2+0) = 36
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Equipment was being returned to Sandia National Laboratories due to termination of a contract with Pacific Scientific (PacSci).  PacSci believed all equipment was free of all hazardous material and generated shipping papers which did not indicate the presence of any hazards.  Equipment was transported in a Budget Rental box van.    Approximately seven months after receipt of equipment and placement in temporary storage, equipment refurbishment revealed approximately 0.061 grams of HNS was present in the filter and motor assembly of one piece of equipment.    No releases, damages, or injuries occurred as a result of this incident. The HNS was safely processed as waste using internal processes.
column169: Pacific Scientific had written procedures which required cleaning of the filter assembly daily.  This apparently was not followed the last day the equipment was used to process HNS.  Pacific Scientific training must be clear to require adherence to their written procedures for prevention of recurrence.

column168: On 06/29/2008 at 03:30, personnel in CSX Transportation (CSXT), Stanley Yard reported that GATX 60998, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, had been observed leaking from its top. column168: Driver stated that oncoming car crossed the center line and forced him off to the shoulder of the road entering a curve. The driver lost control and went of the road and onto its side and slid into a large oak tree. The tree bent the top of the trailer behind the roll over protection and cause it to start a large leak. An earth dike was quickly built in the ditch to prevent the alcohol from reaching a waterway. A power pole was also struck when the truck went off the road so there was concern for the electrical power by the flammable liquid. The spilled material was pumped from the earth dike and returned to the shipper.
column169: We are presenting programs at our quarterly safety meeting for preventing rollovers, choosing good routes that do not have dangerous curves, and reducing speed with tank trailers when entering curves. We feel this was not an equipment failure, but a human error that made this a preventable accident just by reducing speed.

column168: DRIVER/TRUCK EXITING PARKING LOT ONTO ROADWAY; RIGHT-SIDE/PASSENGER-SIDE TRAILER DOLLY SUPPORT LEG SCRAPED AND BECAME GROUNDED TO CONCRETE SIDEWALK. (SIDEWALK WAS AT APEX OF SURFACE AREA AS BOTH THE PARKING LOT AND STREET PAVEMENT DROPPED OFF A SHARP GRADE FROM SIDEWALK. AS THE DOLLY LEG STRUCK THE CONCRETE SIDEWALK, PRESSURE WAS SUCH THAT THE RIGHT-SIDE DOLLY LEG SUPPORT BROKE FREE OF THE TOP MOUNTING AREA AND THE CROSS-BRACE PENETRATED THE BOTTOM OF COMPARTMENT # 2 OF OUR ALUMINUM MC306 TANK TRAILER. THE TRUCK BASICALLY CAME TO A SUDDEN STOP DUE TO THE DOLLY LEG STRIKING THE SIDEWALK; DRIVER THEN EXITED TRACTOR AND NOTED THAT DOLLY LEG WAS GROUNDED ONTO THE SIDEWALK AND THAT HERE WAS SPILLAGE OF GASOLINE COMING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER. DRIVER PLACED CALL TO 911 AS WELL AS OUR TRANSPORTATION OPERATIONS CENTER REGARDING THIS SPILL INCIDENT AND PLACED SOP PADS BENEATH THE LEAK AREA COMING OFF TRAILER BELLY. THE LOCAL DELHI TOWNSHIP, OH FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS INITIAL RESPONDER — THEY CORDONED OFF THE AREA AND WOULD NOT ALLOW DRIVER BACK NEAR THE TRANSPORT UNIT AND THEY MADE DECISION TO LET THE GASOLINE PRODUCT TO COMPLETELY RUN OUT OF THE DAMAGED TRAILER COMPARTMENT. FIRE DEPT DID PLACE ABSORBENT MATERIALS (BOOMS AND ALIKE) AT GRATE AREAS TO THE STORM WATER SEWER THAT WERE ON THE PROPERTY ITSELF AS WELL AS A DRAIN THAT WAS ALSO ON STREET THAT WAS ADJACENT TO THE SITE. FIRE DEPARTMENT INITIATED GENERAL RESIDENTIAL EVACUATION FOR A 1000’ AREA AROUND THE INCIDENT SITE. IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THE STORM WATER DRAINS THAT THE GASOLINE PRODUCT WAS ENTERING INTO 36” MAIN TRUNK LINE FOR THE STORM SEWER SYSTEM. CONSULTATION WITH THE CINCINNATI METROPOLITAN SEWER DISTRICT (CMSD) PERSONNEL RESULTED IN TERMINATION TO “FLUSH” THE SEWER LINE WITH LARGE VOLUMES OF WATER AND TO ALLOW THE CONTAMINANT TO PROCEED TOWARD THE (CMSD) RIVER BASIN AND ON INTO THE OHIO RIVER. DURATION OF THE SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK TRAILER WAS FOR APPROX. 30 MINUTES AS IT WAS COMING OUT OF THE APPROX. 3” HOLE THAT THE CROSS BRACE FROM THE TRAILER DOLLY LEG MADE INTO THE TANKER COMPARTMENT (NOTING THAT THE CROSS-BRACE WAS “FILLING-UP” SOME OF THE 3” DIAMETER HOLE AT THAT TIME AS IT HAD PENETRATED THE TRAILER AND WAS STILL STICKING INTO TRAILER COMPARTMENT — SO A FULL 3” HOLE WAS NOT “OPEN FOR THE SPILLAGE AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL INCIDENT). PHOTO SHOWING TRAILER/DOLLY LEG HUNG-UP ON THE CONCRETE SIDEWALK ENCLOSED AS WELL AS PHOTO SHOWING THE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF TRAILER THAT THE CROSS BRACE HAD MADE)
column169: THE CONFIGURATION OF THE PARKING LOT AND ANGEL OF ROADWAY HARD SURFACES CREATED AN UNUSUAL SITUATION AND CONSENSUS IS THAT DRIVER, ALTHOUGH HE STATED HE HAD A HISTORY OF DELIVERIES INTO THE SITE; MADE AN ERROR IN JUDGMENT AND DID NOT ALLOW FOR PROPER MANEUVERING OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER TRANSPORT OVER SUCH AN OBLIQUE ANGLE THAT THE PARKING LOT SIDEWALK AND STREET BERM PRESENTED — BASICALLY THAT THE ANGEL WAS SUCH THAT THE RESULT WAS THE DOLLY LEG COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE SIDEWALK HARD SURFACE CAUSING THE PROBLEM. UNFORTUNATELY, WE HAVE HAD OCCASION TO HAVE DRIVERS “CATCH” DOLLY LEGS ON SUCH AS RAILROAD CROSSINGS, ROAD AND LOT CURBS, ETC. IN THE PAST; HOWEVER, WE HAVE NEVER HAD THE OCCASION THAT A SUPPORT DID ANYTHING ELSE BUT “BEND” OR BREAK. IN THIS CASE, THE TELL-TELL OF ALL ANGLES, WEIGHTS, DISTANCES, ETC, WERE SUCH THAT WHEN THE DOLLY LEG IMPACTED THE SIDEWALK THE DOLLY LEG BRACE GAVE WAY AT THE UPPER BRACKET AND WENT UP INTO THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER. WE CANNOT ESTABLISH EQUIPMENT FAILURE DIRECTLY. WE WILL ADDRESS THE ISSUE OF CLEARANCE PERSISTENT TO THIS TYPE OF SITUATION IN OUR ON-GOING DRIVER INFORMATIVE TRAINING PROGRAM.

column168: Company reference Pro number is 084-0887776. Released material was identified as Chlorophenols Solid, 6.1, UN2020, PGIII in 16 x 55 gallon steel drums weighing 9577 pounds. The amount released was 1 liter. The material has a melting point of 42 degrees C as described in the MSDS supplied by the consignee. The material is shipped in a solid form but was released as a liquid due to the melting point and the heat in the trailer at the time of the release.  At approximately 21:15 on 19, June, 2008 our trailer returned from local pick up and deliveries in the Parsippany area. Upon arrival to the carrier’s facility the trailer was placed in a door at the carriers dock. When the door was opened an odor was present. The supervisor closed the door immediately and had the trailer moved away from the dock and contacted the carriers safety dept. at approximately 21:30. The supervisor advised of the incident and stated there was an odor throughout the dock and noticeable in the office area. He also stated some employees were complaining due to the odor. All complaints were of a general nature regarding the odor. There were not any complaints of respiratory distress, nausea, skin or eye irritation. No complaints of headache or any other disorientation associated with the product as described in the MSDS.   The carrier immediately called our emergency response contractor at 21:40 and ordered the building be vacated as a precaution. The employees followed the evacuation plan and all departed the building.Each employee was interviewed and refer him or her to our medical facility. All declined and said any slight discomfort was remedied upon moving outside to fresh air. All employees were monitored along with the supervisor at 15-minute intervals for the next hour and all stated no elevation in symptoms and all had returned to their original status prior to the presence of the odor. No one was ever in direct contact with the material.  The emergency response team arrived at 23:50 and departed at 02:00. Their findings were 1-55 gallon drum of 4-Chlorophenol had a small puncture from a nail protruding from the shippers skid causing a 1 liter release. The team donned the required PPE and proceeded with the clean up. The crew removed several skids of drums to get to the leaking drum. The leaking drum was over packed and the trailer decontaminated, the clean up debris was placed in a 17H drum and is currently waiting for pick up and disposal. Both drums were properly labeled and will be picked up by a licensed waste hauler on Tuesday, 8, July, 2008.
column169: This incident was caused by a nail in the bottom of the shippers skid. The nail impacted the drum causing the release. The use of a cardboard barrier between the skid and the drum would have prevented the impact of the nail to the drum. Prior inspection of the skid for protrudung nails would have revealed the exposed nail and also would have eliminated the release.

column168: On June 11, 2008 a tanker truck from Schneider National Inc. was leaving IMTT Bayonne property and turned onto city road east 22nd when the driver, after checking his rear view mirrors and noticed his tires were wet and knowing he did not drive through any puddles, pulled over to the side of the road.  Upon examination he saw product leaking from one of the dome hatches.  An IMTT operations supervisor, who was driving behind the Schneider truck, also pulled over and initiated emergency response procedures after discovering the leak.  IMTT emergency response personnel along with the OSRO personnel responded to the scene and began to place dry sorbant and pads on the paved roadway to absorb the spilled liquid.  The clean up operation continued to the point of origin within the IMTT terminal.  Upon further examination by the Schneider truck driver, he noticed there was no gasket in place within the suspect dome hatch.
column169: It is the responsibility of the driver to perform an inspection of the vehicle and tanker components to ensure the load is properly secured prior to departure. Had this been done the driver may have noticed that the dome gasket was missing and not left the terminal until it was replaced.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF EQUIPMENT USED TO HANDLED AND MOVE HEAVY FREIGHT. WHEN EXITING TRAILERS TOTES OR BULK PACKAGES, CONTAINING LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE SHROUDED USING CUSHIONS OF DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD, MTY PALLETS OR AIR BAGS TO PREVENT HEAVY OBJECTS FROM FALLING ON TOP AND EASILY DAMAGING TOTES. ALSO, PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE TOTES OR HEAVY MACHINERY TO PREVENT FROM SHIFTING WHILE INTRANSIT, FALLING OVER AND BECOMING DAMAGED. USE DUNNAGE, LOADLOCK BARS, PLYWOOD, MTY PALLETS AND OR AIR BAGS SECURE LOADS. column169: ISSUED OF WARNING LETTER AND APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE, WITH REVIEWS AND INSTRUCTIONS ON SAFE PROCEDURES REGARDING PROPER UNLOADING, LOADING AND HANDLING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FREIGHT. RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALSI PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, Mfl PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: On June 14, 2008 a Veolia employee was preparing paperwork for a hazardous materials shipment at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility located in Latham, NY.  The employee was notified, by a third party driver, that a liquid substance was leaking from a Veolia vehicle on to the asphalt containment that the vehicle was parked on to. The vehicle was parked in transit in temporary storage at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility in Latham, NY.  Approximately 5 gallons of a solution of aluminum sulfate had leaked through a tear in the liner of the cubic yard fiberboard box.  The torn liner was sealed and all liquid inside the cubic yard box was absorbed with speedi-dry and absorbant pads.  The material that had leaked onto the floor of the vehicle and asphalt containment was cleaned up with speedi-dry and absorbant pads.  The clean-up materials were placed into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.
column169: It was determined this spill was caused by a tear in the cubic yard box liner due to a sharp edge of solid aluminum sulfate.  In the future, the use of a second liner will lessen the risk of other incidents.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 2566 GALLONS INTO A TANK THAT STICK GAUGING INDICATED WOULD HOLD 2605 GALLONS. DRIVER WAS DELIVERING THROUGH A REMOTE FILL WHEN PRODUCT BACKED-UP STICK HOLE TUBE AND POPPED-OFF CAP & COVER AND 23 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE FORECOURT. DRIVER CONTAINED MOST OF THE PRODUCT WITH SPILL KIT. SMALL AMOUNT ENTERED TWO STORM DRAINS. SPILL CONTRACTOR AND FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED. LEAVES AND DIRT IN BOTH STORM DRAINS HAD ABSORBED SPILLED PRODUCT. FIRE MARSHALL TESTED SEWER LINES FOR VAPORS AFTER LEAVES AND DIRT WERE REMOVED. THEY TESTED NEGATIVE. SPILL CONTRACTOR FINISHED CLEAN UP OF SITE REMOVING ABSORBENT SPILL KIT MATERIAL AND OIL DRY.
column169: DRIVER ROUTE CARD/STATION LAYOUT INDICATED EMERGENCY OVER FILL WAS SET AT 95% TANK CAPACITY. INSPECTION OF BALL FLOAT SHUT-OFF INDICATED IT WAS SET AT 90% TANK CAPACITY SITE ROUTE CARD TANK CHARTS WERE CHANGED TO 90% AND A METAL MORE SECURE LOCK DOWN CAP WAS PUT ON STICK TUBE.

column168: PALLET WAS LOADED IN RAPID CITY AT VITRAN DOCK, KEGS WERE OVER HANGING PALLET. PALLET WAS PUSHED INTO PALLET IN FRONT OF IT, CAUSING METAL RING ON BOTTOM OF KEG TO BEND. WHEN RING BENT THE BOTTOM OF KEG POPPED OPEN CAUSING ABOUT A 3 INCH LONG GAP IN KEG, ABOUT 1/2 OF 40 LB KEG SIFTED OUT. WHEN UNLOADING PALLET IN SIOUX FALLS THE LEAK WAS NOTICED AND WE PULLED LEAKING KEG OUT OF PALLET. WE SWEPT UP ALL POWDER AND POURED IT BACK INTO ORIGINAL KEG. WE THEN COMPLETELY WRAPPED KEG IN SHRINK WRAP TO CONTAIN POWDER. THE WRAPPED KEG WAS THEN PUT INTO AN OVERPACK CONTAINER, AND LABELED.
column169: DRIVER WHO CAUSED INCIDENT WAS ISSUED A NEEDS FOR IMPROVEMENT. A SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD IN BOTH THE SIOUX FALLS AND RAPID CITY TERMINALS EXPLAINING THE PROPER HANDLING OF SMOKELESS POWDER AND OTHER HAZMAT MATERIALS. THE SHIPER WAS CONTACTED AND WAS TOLD WE WOULD NO LONGER EXCEPT PALLETS WITH KEGS OVER HANGING SIDES. ALSO REQUIRING THEM TO PLACE CARDBOARD UNDER ALL KEG TO PROTECT THEM ON PALLETS.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: MR. KETTMAN RECEIVED A CALL FROM INFOTRAC REGARDING A LOAD OF SAFETY-KLEEN (S-K) WASTE IN A VAN TRAILER. INFOTRAC STATED THE TRANSPORTER IS ROBBIE D. WOOD, INC. WHO IS LOCATED AT THE PILOT TRUCK STOP OFF OF HWY 71 AT EXIT 28 IN PENDLETON, KY INFOTRAC STATED THE TRAILER IS LEAKING ACID FROM THE REAR DOORS. MR. KETTMAN CONTACTED THE DRIVER MR. STAN WATERS WHO STATED HIS SHIPPING DOCUMENTS INDICATE A CORROSIVE A CORROSIVE SOLID AND NOT A LIQUID. MR. KETTMAN CONTACTED EVERGREEN ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP. THE EVERGREEN CREW STATED THE VAN TRAILER HAD BEEN LOADED WITH MARION BAG OR SUPER SAC'S OF A CORROSIVE SOLID. THE CREW STATED THAT ONE OF THE BAGS HAD SOME MOIST MATERIAL WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF THE LIQUID. THE CREW UTILIZED ACID PADS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO STOP AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE. THE EVERGREEN PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE S-K FACILITY IN SMITHFIELD, KY AND WERE GRANTED AN EARLY DISPOSAL TIME DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE INCIDENT. THE EVERGREEN PERSONNEL STATED THE RELEASED AMOUNTED TO 1 GALLON WHICH COVERED AN AREA 2 FOOT WIDE AND 3 FEET LONG ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE EVERGREEN PERSONNEL HAD GENERATED 1-5 GALLON PAIL OF NEUTRALIZED CLEANUP DEBRIS WHICH HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO EVERGREENS LOCATION FOR STAGING UNTIL S-K CAN MADE ARRANGEMENT TO HAVE THE PAIL REMOVED. THE CREW STATED THE SUPER SAC DID NOT FAIL. THE SUPER SAC'S ARE DESIGNED FOR DRY MATERIAL NOT MOIST OR WET MATERIAL. THE LARGE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL IN THE BAG CAUSED THE  MOIST MATERIAL TO WEEP THROUGH THE SAC AND ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND OUT THE REAR DOORS.
column169: IN THE FUTURE THE WASTE MATERIAL CAN EITHER BE PLACE INTO POLY DRUMS OR PLACE A POLY LINER IN THE SUPER SAC PRIOR TO LOADING MATERIAL. THE BEST SOLUTION IS TO ENSURE THE WASTE MATERIAL IS 100% DRY BEFORE PLACING IT INTO A NON LIQUID CONTAINER.

column168: A vinegar odor was reported in the railyard and CELX 3263 (a residue Acetic Anhydride DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was the suspect source of this odor. BNSF contract responders inspected CELX 3263 and reported finding the vacuum relief valve (VRV) emanating a product vapor hiss. The responders tried to close the VRV, but the vapor hiss continued. Responders removed the VRV and applied/secured a four bolt blind flange plate over the vacated VRV orifice, ending any further vapor release. No liquid product was released. Response was concluded by 1330 hrs. CDT, 6/15/08. The removed VRV was returned to the tank car owner for failure analysis.   The specification stencil on CELX 3263 indicated that its last Tank Qualification was completed in the year 2002 and is next due in 2012.

column168: Driver discovered paint leaking from bottom of trailer. First Response was dispatched to scene for cleanup. Original drum and waste as collected and placed in recovery drum for disposal by First Response.

A BNSF carman inspecting railcars in the railyard, reported TILX 318595 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from its top fitting area onto its side shell with no ground impact. TILX 318595 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. A BNSF inspection revealed that the valve housing cover was not sealed and the product trail appeared to originate at the base of the valves. A shipper contract responder reported that all valves were properly closed. The mounting flange nuts at the base of the 3 1/2 inch loading/liquid valve were found to be only hand tight and the mounting flange nuts at the base of the vacuum relief valve were less than tool tight. All flange nuts were properly tool tightened. The non-evaporated product spillages at the base of the valves and also at the top of the tank car shell were wiped. Response was concluded by 1730 hrs. PDT, 6/23/08. No further product release was noted during subsequent TILX 318595 movements.

column168: CARRIER ARRIVED AT DEL CAMINO SERVICE PLAZA TO HAVE HIS PRODUCT HEATED UP TO ACCOMODATE CUSTOMER DELIVERY TEMPERTURE.  CAMINO HOOKED THIER HOT WATER LINE TO SUPERIORS TRAILER AND LINES WERE IMPROPERLY OPENED AND CAUSED PRESSURE ON TRAILER THROUGH THE HEATING PROCESS AND CAUSED THE TANK TO CRACK.  TRAILER LOST PRODUCT THROUGH THE HEATING LINES THAT DRIPPED INTO A DRUM UNTIL THE TRANSLOADING OF THE PRODUCT COULD OCCUR.      RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ASSISTED DRIVERS WHILE THE TRANSLOADING PROCESS TOOK PLACE AND THEY REMOVED THE DRUM CONTAINING THE DRIPPNG PROUCT.
column169: TRAILERS ARE NORMALLY HEATED AT TANKWASHES WITH STEAM.  THIS WAS THE ONLY TANKWASH IN THE DENVER AREA AND THEY COULD HEAT WITH HOT WATER ONLY.  FUTURE LOADS THAT HAVE THE HOT WATER OPTION ONLY, DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO CALL HOME TERMINAL TO ENSURE THE TANKWASH HAS KNOWLEDGE OF HOW TO PROPERLY HANDLE OUR EQUIPMENT PROPERLY SO THIS TYPE OF ERROR WILL NOT BE REPEATED.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On June 30, 2008, at approximately 0830 hours, a railway tankcar SCMX 4311, loaded with Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. Combustible Liquid, UN1268 PG III, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Wylie Texas yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the top of the car. The vacuum relief valve was was completely removed from manway cover. Calumet at Cotton Valley, LA loaded the car and applied all closures and placed car in transportation. Per operating agreement, Calumet loaded the car and Shell by contract shown as shipper.The shipper representative responded to the site, teflon taped and installed the vacuum relief valve to the manway cover correcting the release point. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.        CODE: 466  NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(2+0)=60
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.      NARRI: 5(5+5+1)x(2+0)=60  CODE: 466

column168: On June 27, 2008 at about 07:50, personnel in the CSXT Wildwood yard discovered PSPX 23588, a loaded tank car of Dicyclopentadiene, leaking from around the manway cover. The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Phillips, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report  # 2008-06-27-00033). SWS First Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the manway cover gasket was missing. Contractor personnel installed a new manway cover gasket and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  207  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On June 30th at 18:18, FRA Inspector David Schwake was inspecting rail cars at the CSXT's Henry Street Yard in Spartanburg, South Carolina.  During his inspection he discovered UTLX48183, a residue tank car of Other Regulated Substances, Liquid, N.O.S. (Ethylene Glycol) dripping product from the bottom outlet valve stem.  Inspector Schwake notified local management and the area around the rail car was isolated.  The shipper, Invista SARL was contacted and requested to respond and secure the container.  Invista representatives were successful in containing the release of product, however were unable to properly repair the bottom outlet valve stem packing.  Since the car no longer complied with DOT specifications the shipper, Invista SARL applied for a FRA Movement Approval.  Upon receiving notice of approval (FRA-08070217) the car was released to destination.  Approximately 1 gallon was released from the container.  Cause Code: 510  NARRI: 2(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 20

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was loading fuel at a client site. As the driver began to load he hooked the riser to compartment 4 (1000 liquid gallon capacity) although he though he hooked the riser to compartment 1 (3000 liquid gallon capacity). At approximately 962 gallons he realized his error and attempted to stop the pump. The pump failed to stop so driver pulled out his scully cord, the pump still failing to stop. Driver then immediately hit the emergency shut off but approximately 25-30 gallons had leaked from the top of the hatch. The spill was contained on concrete and did not enter soil or drains. The spill was cleaned up by in-house personnel. The site was cleaned up to the satisfaction of terminal operator, Tommy and site terminal manager, Sandra.
column169: Driver needs to double check all hookups prior to starting the loading or unloading process. Driver will watch a training video for loading and unloading as well as have a Safety Manager perform an incident prevention observation on him.

column168: On June 30, 2008 at 11:40 FRA Inspector Mel Massaro in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered PLMX 135547, a loaded tank car of Ammonia Anhydrous leaking from inside the protective housing. The area around the car was isolated and CSXT Hazmat, PCS Sales, Maryland Department of the Environment, Cumberland Fire Department  were notified. Specializied Professional Services Inc., a CSXT response contractor, was also dispatched to the scene. CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager found on the Pressure Relief Valve  the O ring Assembly had a minor vapor release. CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager along with SPSI changed out the O ring assembly and resecured the PRV and the vapor release was mitigated. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    Chemtrec Report Number 2008063000094  Cause Code:  414  NARRI:  2(5+9+0) X (2+0) = 56

column168: After a BNSF train arrival at the Thayer, MO railyard, the outbound BNSF crew was in the process of changing the locomotive consist (due to the lead locomotive having mechanical problems) and cut away from the train consist. The unattended train consist rolled south down grade onto the main track where it struck the head end of a northbound BNSF train which was stopped on the single main track. This impact resulted in ACFX 47712 (a three compartment covered hopper ) in the roll-out consist derailing on its side and sustaining a three foot long gash into the B-end hopper compartment releasing product. Also, the B-end top hatchway sprung open and released product. The spilled product was vacuumed up and earmarked for appropriate landfill disposal. The remaining product in ACFX 47712 was placed into roll-off boxes and later transferred into trucks for delivery to the consignee.

column168: When loading fiber drums into trailer forklift operator was placing a drum next to another drum already staged in the trailer. When he placed the drum next to the other one he pushed it tight and when doing so the weight of the forklift slightly ruptured the seam of the fiber drum contributing to the unintentional release.Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged drum.

During railyard switching activities, the lead railcars in a shove movement rolled away from the shove cut of railcars into a yard track striking unattended railcars already in this track. The impact resulted in UTLX 64959 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) standing in the yard track derailing on its side with a puncture hole on the A-end tank head at the 3 to 4 o'clock position spilling product. Responders plugged the puncture hole with wooded plugs and plastic which reduced the product release and UTLX 64959 was up righted. The product release ended by 0100 hrs. CDT on 6/06/08 after the product within reached the area below the tank head compromise. The spilled product was contained in a drainage ditch parallel to the yard track. Soda ash and citric acid were applied to the ground impact area to neutralize spillage. Ground remediation and monitoring is ongoing after a series of rain events that followed the derailment. The remaining product in UTLX 64959 was transferred into poly tanks for future appropriate disposal.

column168: A TANKER TRUCK CARRYING FUEL HYDROCARBONS OVERTURNED WHILE TRAVELING ON STATE HIGHWAY 40 AT MILE MARKER 200.5 APPROXIMATELY 1.5 MILES WEST OF HOT SULPHUR SPRINGS, COLORADO. THE TANKER FAILED TO NEGOTIATE A CURVE IN THE HIGHWAY, OVERTURNED, AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND 5,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CDOT INITIALLY. BASED ON VISUAL OBSERVATION, IT APPEARS THAT THE DIESEL FUEL MIGRATED APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET VIA OVERLAND FLOW DOWN THE SLOPE ON THE WESTERN SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY TOWARDS THE COLORADO RIVER BEFORE STOPPING. FUEL DID NOT REACH THE RIVER AT THAT TIME. THE GASOLINE APPEARS TO HAVE FLOWED TOWARD THE CLIFFSIDE OF THE ROAD TO THE EAST WHERE IT PONDED AND EVENTUALLY INFILTRATED.

column168: A residue product odor was reported emanating from GATX 23329 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 23329 and determined that the odor source was from the manway closure of GATX 23329. No liquid product release was evident. No seals were present at the manway and the valve housing cover. Four of the six manway securement bolts were found to be only hand tight. The manway gasket was dirty, compressed and cut in two places. With assistance from BNSF contract responders, a new manway gasket was applied and the manway cover was properly secured. GATX 23329 was monitored and no further residue product odor was detectable. Response was concluded by 2200 hrs. CDT, 6/28/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was in route to deliver a load of Ethanol to a client location. While in transit the driver was motioned to pull over by a civillian car. Upon doing so our driver noticed a leak near the belly vailve in compartment 2. Driver immediately utilized his boom/spill kit to contain spill. The driver used putty to minimize the spill but was unsuccessful due to the pressure in the tank. The remaining product was pumped to another trailer but it was determined that approximately 243 gallons did leak. The Osceola Fire Department, SWS and Highway Patrol all repsonded to the incident and assisted with clean up.
column169: It was determined that there was a leak in the weld/cross member near the belly valve. Tank will be repaired by replacing part and inspected by shop personnel. Incident will also be dicussed in monthly safety meeting.

column168: Driver, Alan Choate, loaded cargo tank vehicle (#224) for gasoline delivery to Columbia Liberty station. Driverproceeded toward Columbia MD traveling on MD Rt2 (Hanover Street) to 1-95 SB on ramp. Vehicle entered onto ramp, cargo tank began to roll to right side, as vehicle crested incline of ramp cargo tank vehicle rolled over on rightside. Driver escaped vehicle, stopped traffic, contacted 911 and Petro Express Co. officials. Baltimore City FireDepartment, Baltimore City Police and Maryland Department of Environment Emergency Response Units responded distributed spill retaining booms and absorbent pads. Cargo Tank was damaged on right side and top of barrel. TheNo.1 compartment shell was gouged allowing 708gals. of gasoline to drain onto the roadway, run down a runoff andonto the ground beneath the ramp (CSX railroad switching station yard). Miller Environmental Co. responded torecover all contaminated area.
column169: Petro Express Co. and it's Insurance Carrier has re-trained the drivers with a 2 hour training session including a video, handbook and quiz on cargo tank motor vehicle roll over prevention.

column168: A citizen reported to CHEMTREC that PROX 42034 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the BNSF railyard was observed with a fresh product stain on the side shell that appeared to be emanating from this tank car's "dome" area. A BNSF mechanical responder was notified and inspected PROX 42034. The responder reported finding the liquid valve's closure cap less than tool tight with the valve handle loose and possibly not in the fully closed position. The handle was tightened, the valve was closed and the closure cap was tool tightened by 2030 hrs. PDT 6/23/08. No further product release was observed after this securement was completed. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident. PROX 42034 was directed to a qualified repair facility after it was unloaded for a detailed inspection of the liquid valve since product may have bypassed the valve when in the closed position.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Preventable Spill.  Failed to connect hose to UST, opened valve- loss of 39 gal NL to storm drain and creek.  Response by FD, PD, NC DENR.  Report to NRC & US EPA. Clean Water act violation.    Inventory reconciliation determined that 39 gallons of gasoline were released to the concrete and asphalt surface at the site from Eagle Transport's fuel delivery truck. Some of the fuel entered a nearby storm drain on Park Road. It was determined that this storm drain eventually discharges to Little Sugar Creek approximately 450 yards east of this store. No free product is present at this time. The release was discovered immediately by the driver of the fuel delivery truck.    NC Emergency Management Notification: 6-20-0804:24 Notified; June 20, 2008 at 4:24 pm    NRC Incident Number: 874791 Notified; June 20, 2008 at 4:35 pm    Release Source: Release from fuel delivery truck during delivery to gas station. column168: On June 23, 2008, Midwest Environmental personnel arrived on site to perform cleanup and remediation activities.  The contractor began by assessing the situation and preparing an appropriate course of action.  They utilized a vacuum truck to remove the product from the storm drain.  OEPA officials were on site and had tracked the material through the storm sewer system.  The contractor worked with OEPA and the Dayton Fire Department to flush the storm drains and remove the water from the system.  The pH of the original drain was at 14 when the contractor arrived on site and was declared clear by the OEPA at 12 after several hours of flushing the system and neutralizing the storm sewer with citric acid.  The contractor used granular absorbents to remove the product from the impacted area of the parking lot.  The absorbents were swept from the parking surface and containerized for disposal.  On June 24, 2008, the contractor returned to the site to complete remediation of the impacted area.  They used citric acid and their vacuum truck to remove residual product that was contained in the cracks in the asphalt.  A small area of soil had been impacted by the release and was excavated to remove the contamination.  The area was backfilled and graded to original condition.

Driver had made connections to transfer product from cargo tank to the customer's storage tank.  He started the flow very slowly so he could check for any problems before he opened the valve all the way.  As soon as the product hit a straight PVC connection between the customers hook up fitting and the check valve for the storage tank, product started to leak out.  The connection had come loose.  Driver immediately stopped the flow of product.  The customer cleaned up the spill.
column169: The customer repaired the line and the product was scheduled for redelivery.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was unloading at a client location. While standing near the hosed the driver was alerted by the terminal operator that there seemed to be a leak. The driver immediately shut of the main valves and flow of product but approximately 10-15 gallons leaked onto concrete area, no product reached soil or drains. The leak came from the inlet hose and after investigation it was determined that the band clamps on the inlet hose were weak and had actually come loose, causing the spill. The spill was cleaned up by driver and terminal personnel.
column169: Terminal personnel at client facility replaced faulty band clamps on inlet hose. This was check prior to next delivery.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: WHILE SORTING A GROUND PACKAGE TO BE LOADED VEHICLE DESIRED FOR INMETCO AS PART OF THE RECHARGEABLE BATTERY RECYCLING COMPANY PROGRAM (RBRC), A SORT EMPLOYEE NOTICED EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID SPILL WITHIN THE PACKAGE. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THE BOX CONTAINED A SPILLABLE ACID BATTERY, PROHIBITED IN THE RBRC PROGRAM AND OUT OF COMPLIANCE WITH THE HMRS. THE PACKAGE DID NOT DISPLAY CORRECT HAZARD MARKINGS OR HAZARD LABEL, AND IT WAS NOT ACCOMPANIED BY A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING PAPER.
column169: UPS CONTACTED RBRC FOR FOLLOW-UP  WITH THE ORGINATOR OF THE SHIPMENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: While sorting packages for delivery to Inmetco, an employee noticed evidence of leakage on the exterior of a package from the Rechargeable Battery recycling Program (RBRC). On investigation, the package was found to contain four spillable batteries. The acid from one or more of the batteries had leaked during package handling and contaminated the outer fiberboard. The package was prepared in non-compliance with the RBRC program and the HMRs. There was no marking, labeling for the contents and the shipment was not accompanied by a hazardous materials shipping paper.
column169: UPS HAS NOTIFIED RBRC OF THE INCIDENT FOR FOLLOW-UP WITH THE PROGRAM PARTICIPANT.

column168: FILE-08-62 DOT &OMC SHIPPER-LORD & TAYLOR AWB#-AVP 18623344434 ETWON 06/18/2008 AT 1630 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE MANASQUAN DHL EXPRESS STATION, LOCATED AT 2271 LANDMARK PLACE, MANASQUAN, NJ 08736. MAUREEN FROM THE MANASQUAN DHL EXPRESS STATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD AN ODOROUS SHIPMENT. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 9 X 4.2 OZ GLASS BOTTLES OF POLO COLOGNE. DUE TO 4 OF THE GLASS BOTTLES BEING BROKEN, A TOTAL OF 12 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE MANASQUAN DHL EXPRESS STATION VIA TRUCK # 5169.THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. WE RECEIVED A MSDS SHOWING THE DOT DESCRIPTION AS CONSUMER COMMODITY, LIMITED QUANTITY, BUT UNDER SP9275. LOREAL IS THE MANUFACTURER AND THEY USE THE EXEMPTION, BUT THE SHIPPER LORD AND TAYLOR, WAS NOT LOCATED ON THE EXEMPTION LIST AS USING THE EXEMPTION.CLEAR OF SCENE: 2222 EST.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A TOTE OF LIQUID WAS FOUND LEAKING DUE TO A FAULTY VALVE FOUND LOOSE. PER SHIPPER’S RECOMMENDATION AND AUTHORIZATION, A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REPAIRED THE VALVE AND THE TOTE WAS OKAYED AND FORWARD ONTO CONSIGNEE. A LINED SALVAGE DRUMS OF CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE DRUM IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS, VALVES AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: WHILE ENROUTE TO DESTINATION.  A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID WAS FOUND LEAKING AND DAMAGED, DUE TO IT WAS PUNCTURED BY A SHARP OBJECT.  THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WILL BE HANDLED BY THE ER TEAM FOR PROPER DISPOSITION.
column169: DRUMS CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN! ALDRUMS MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT AND FALLING OVER WHILE UNIT IS MOVING. USE LOAD LOCKBARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCKBARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF! RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: Driver left Lancaster terminal around 15:30 heading to Red Bank, NJ to deliver to Meridian Hospital.  Driver drove down PA turnpike to NJ turnpike (where he was stuck in stop and go traffic) to Rt. 195 east to Rt. 18 north.  After going a short distance on Rt. 18 north, the driver noticed a vapor cloud at the rear of his trailer.  The driver looked for a place to pull over and chose an area where an entrance ramp joined in with Rt. 18 and he could position the unit on the shoulder of the entrance ramp to keep the unit as far as possible from the main road.  Upon investigation, the driver found a small liquid leak and vapor cloud at the rear of the trailer.  He cautiously opened the rear cabinet doors to verify the leak was the bottom fill and tired to close it further with his valve wrench.  He was unsuccessful in this attempt and noticed the LOX was dripping directly onto the macadam he was parked on.  He then called EST and was directed to get water to thaw and tighten the bottom fill valve.  At this time a local police officer arrived on scene and told our driver he was not to get near the rear of our trailer and that he had called HAZMAT.  Our driver tried to explain what was needed to be done to get the valve closed, but was refused access to our vehicle.  HAZMAT arrived on scene and promptly closed the northbound lanes of Rt. 18.  The APCI Crisis team was activated and contact was made with the HAZMAT team onsite.  The FCV was tripped to try and stop the leak, but the HAZMAT team was unable to verify the leak was stopped.  After further discussion, it was suggested that water be used to thaw out the valve and this did prove successful in stopping the leak (which is what the driver wanted to do initially).  The whole unit was towed to APCI Manalapan per the request of the HAZMAT/police after it was determined that the tire and running gear were serviceable.  The following morning an inspection was completed on both the running gear and valve piping before the trailer was released to return to Lancaster site.
column169: Trailer is being sent to rehab for further evaluation and valve replacement.  Initial inspection of valve shows no signs of wear.

column168: A Van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the vehicle was stopped at Clean Harbor’s in-transit storage facility located in Santa Clara, CA. While at this location, it was noted that a small amount of material had escaped from the van trailer onto the ground directly beneath the trailer. Facility personnel immediately notified local management and the emergency response procedures were activated. IN addition, notification was made to the appropriate state agency. Facility personnel, using appropriate personnel protective equipment entered the trailer and discovered that a small crack had developed at the seam of the drum allowing approximately 15 gallons of material to escape onto the floor of the van trailer. The container was placed into a suitable salvage drum long with all clean-up debris collected from the van trailer floor and the ground underneath the trailer. This container, once secured was placed back on the trailer and was disposed of at the intended waste management facility.
column169: Subsequent to the initial response activities, information pertaining to the waste stream involved was reviewed. The material was profiled for disposal as a hazardous waste liquid material though it did contain small percentages of both inorganic acids and inorganic bases that were incorporated into the waste stream as a result of the waste generation process. It was expected that the process generating this waste stream resulted in a waste stream that was not corrosive. One possible cause of the drum failure is that the percentages of acids and bases in this specific drum were elevated allowing a reaction to degrade the basic packaging material of the container allowing a crack to develop. Though we are not certain this was the cause, we have suspended the waste stream until additional information is obtained certifying that contents of the waste stream. It is important to note that at the time of loading, the driver inspected the containers and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Our drivers will continue to inspect each container and will take appropriate corrective actions should a container of suspect condition be observed.

THE THEN LOST CONTROL AND CONTINUE EASTBOUND ACROSS THE WESTBOUND LANE STRIKING A GUARDRAIL ON NORTH SIDE OF ROAD. ONCE THE TRUCK STRUCK THE GUARDRAIL IT APPEARS THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER THE GUARDRAIL CRUSHING THE CAB, PUNCTURING ONE COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK AND DAMAGING ONE OF THE COMPARTMENT LIDS. THE PUNCTURE CAUSED MUST OF THE PRODUCT IN THAT COMPARTMENT TO BE RELEASED INTO THE SOIL BELOW. ALSO, THE DISLODGING OF THE COMPARTMENT LID CAUSED A LEAK THAT WENT TO THE SOIL BENENTH THE LID. column168: On 6-19-2008 the BNSF Railroad finished the delivery of fifteen rail cars at 11:45 am. At 11:50 am the ACTIcontractor during checking in the railcars noticed the car was leaking and informed the Terminal Operator assigned toRail Cars. The Operator informed the office and two of the Office Personnel responded.12:02 Terminal Superintendent was notified. He had the Fire Dept called and told the T.O. to radio Lubes personnelto evacuate. 12:05 Area Manager was notified. T.S. in route from Atwood Terminal to Vernon.12:00 pm Lube Facility was informed to close their section of the service road and the service road along theirwarehouse. Distribution side closed their service road and initiated the call to the Vernon Fire Department. (WindSpeed low to the EAST picked up speed later to above 5mph to the EAST)Fire Dept on site 12:07, Terminal Loading Rack Operation Shutdown. Fire Dept changed staging area from serviceroad near TK #4 to west side of Lube Facility to stage upwind.Coordinate with Fire Department on best way to vent the rail car and relieve thermal pressure.T.S. had another FLS respond to site, given he was closer to Terminal.12:46 pm BNSF Representatives onsite12:57 pm Fire Department hoses and foam buckets staged and area foamed. (Spill containment tray foamed andunderside of rail car.)1:09 pm Rail car vented and leaking plug tightened to stop the flow of ethanol by the Fire Department. The fill tubeball valve was left partially open and the plug for the vent ball valve was loose. Fire personnel tightened plug fiveturns till hand tight and three turns till tool tight. The car was sealed and not tampered with, (per Fire Dept.)

Driver was completeing the loading process and securing the dome lid and other closures, however, he only partial closed the vent valve on top of cargo tank. Driver proceeded to exit loading facility and headed east on US Highway 60 when he noticed acid leaking from the trailer. Driver parked vehicle on side of roadway and made notifications. Company personnel arrived on-scene, inspected trailer, and determined source of leak was from partially closed vent valve. Valve was closed, cargo tank and roadway were cleaned by environmental response contractor and driver proceeded to destination.
column169: Investigation revealed driver's training was up to date and the required inspection checklist was used. Driver was returned to training with driver trainer for an additional two days.

column168: DSR William Shaughnessy was making a pick up at Star Pipe Llc,13605 52ND ST E, SUMNER, WA, 98390, When he opened the back of his trailer he noticed the rope used to tie in four praxair cylinders PRO#842-1 28501 (Helium,Refrigerated Liquid 2.2 Non-Flammable Gas UN1963)had frayed and snapped and one of the cylinders was on its side leaking out the valve. This shipment was loaded and signed on by New Dock Hire Steve Zuerlein Employee ID 52242. William immediately called me and explained the situation. I then called CHEMTREC 1-800-424-9300 and they informed me to keep the trailer ventilated due to a decrease in oxygen from the helium in the air and to stand the tank upright if possible. William kept the trailer door opened for ventilation and stood the cylinder upright. The valve froze over and stopped leaking. William placed all four cylinders in the nose of his trailer and tied them to the walls and put plywood up and a load bar to secure the shipment. CHEMTREC referred me to a Praxair Representative named Andy who told me that the cylinder needs to be reweighed and depending on the weight it should be fine to deliver. The gross weight of the cylinder was 3841bs after reweighing the spilled shipment it weighed 345lbs. Per Andy OK for Tranport and delivery to the customer.
column169: New Dock Hire Steve Zuerlein will be retrained on proper loading of Hazmat. A conference Report will be created on proper hazmat loading and use of rope on the dock.

column168: One plastic jug in a cardtboard carton with 4 jugs in it, had a loose cap that released fumes causing the cardboard carton to become brittle and began todecompose the cardboard. The bottom was falling apart. As a result of the shipment movement in trailers and the special handling required by the ctn falling apart, theliguid began to leak past the loose cap, saturating one comer of the carton. The wet carton was removed from the route trailer and isolated. Conway manager ofSafety was informed. Contact was established with Chemtrec, Kevin, report number 2008062500157 and Ned Patthoff with the shipper, Ecolab. Conway FOS cleanedup the spill following the instructions of both Chemtrec and Ecolab, using eye protection and gloves. The consignee has agreed to accept the one jug now that is itrecooped, clean and in good condition
column169: Inspect all cartons of muriatic acid, ecolab item 19890 before accepting a shipment. Both Ned Patthoff from Ecolab and Heide Vollmer at the consignee were familiarwith this condition. The cardboard turns brittle when exposed to the fumes. It will be easy to determine if thereis a loose cap inside.

column168: Our driver unloaded this load into the customer's storage tank that was inside a building out of our driver's line of sight.  Our driver had the receiver review the shipper's bill of lading to review the product and quantity before unloading.  The plant operator signed our disclaimer stating that there was ample room in their storage tank to receive this product.      Customer's storage tank was connected to another storage tank with a line so product could equalize between the two tanks but the storage tank failed to equalize and overfilled spilling approximately 50 gallons of product.
column169: The operator who normally unloads this product was off when this happen so it was this specific operator's first time to unload this material.  It is possible that additional training may have prevented this incident unless the line used to equalize the product in the two tanks was plugged for some reason.

column168: ON 6/30/08 AT 0449 HRS. A SWITCHING CREW IN COTTON WHSE YARD DETECTED AN ODOR AND SAW PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE TOP OF CAR CHVX292047. IT CONTAINED PETROLEUM PRODUCTS NOS, A CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN1268. THEY NOTIFIED THE YARD MASTER WHO NOTIFIED THE STATE POLICE AND NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPT. THE TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED ME AND I CALLED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE. UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY DETERMINED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS LEAKING. HE TIGHTENED THE VALVE BUT IT WAS STILL LEAKING PAST THE VALVE. THEY RELEASED THE PRESSURE OFF THE TANK AND PULLED THE SLUG, CLEANED THE THREADS AND REINSTALLED THE PLUG. THEY CHECKED THE CAR FOR LEAKS AND DETECTED NONE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1030 HRS. THE STATE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED THAT THE INCIDENT WAS CLOSED OUT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0645 ON JUNE 30,2007 A TRACTOR TRAILER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON RTE 895 BETWEEN BERGER CREEK AND DINKEY ROAD, NEAR PALMERTON, PA 18071. ROADWAY IS TWO LANE WITH NO EMERGENCY LANE AND LITTLE ROAD SHOULDER. TRACTOR TRAILER LEFT ROADWAY AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO RETURN TO ROADWAY AND IN DOING SO, STRUCK/BRUSHED TWO TELEPHONE UTILITY POLES AND CONCRETE BRIDGE ABUTMENT. TRAILER TANDEM AXLES WERE DISLODGED AND TRAILER VESSEL RECIEVED MINOR CUT/GOUGE, ALLOWING SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE TO ROADWAY. FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL INCLUDINGA CALL TO 911 AND THE CONTACT OF OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CLEANUP CONTRACTORS, EWMI-RAPID RESPONSE, INC. AND ALSO ELK ENVIRONMENTAL. RAPID RESPONSE, INC. INITIATED AND DIRECTED THE CLEAN-UP AND REMEDIATION EFFORTS RELATED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ALL MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY PACKAGED AT THE SITE AND TRANSPORTED FROM THE SCENE FOR SHIPMENT TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE. THE FOLLOWING RESPONDED TO THE SCENE: PPL ELECTRIC, PADEP, CARBON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT COORDINATOR, PA STATE POLICE, EAST PENN TOWNSHIP POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT, V&M TOWING AND F.T. SILFIES, INC. MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL.
column169: BASED ON THE REPORTS TAKEN ON THE SCENE, THE INCIDENT WAS GENERALLY CAUSED BY THE TRACTOR TRAILER DRIFTING OFF THE ROADWAY AND EXPERIENCING DIFFICULTY ON BERM WHILE ATTEMPTING TO RE-ENTER ROADWAY. THE EDGE OF THE ROAD IS VERY NARROW AND A SIGNIFICANT DROP-OFF WAS PRESENT ALONG THE ROADWAY (SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS). IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT THE ROAD EDGE BE WIDENED AND STRENGTHENED TO PRVENT THE LIKELIHOOD OF ROLLOVER.
