column168: THE DRIVER ENTERED THE RAMP TO EXT 339 FROM I-270 EAST. THE RAMP CURVES TO THE RIGHT, THEN TURN SHARPLY TO THE LEFT AS IT CLIMBS TO ARE OVERPASS CROSSING I-276. AS HE WENT INTO THE LEFT TURN THE TRUCK BEGAN TO ROLL TO THE RIGHT. THE DRIVER TRIED TO COMPENSATE BY STEELING ENTLY TO THE LEFT. THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, SLID FORWARD INTO  THE GUARDRAIL, CRUSHING THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE CAB AND IMPADING ON THE BULKHEAD OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIER CLIMED OUT OF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAB. EMERGENCY 911 WAS CALLED. THE FT. WASHINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE TANKER HAD NOT BEEN PUNCTURED BUT PRODUCT SOON BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE VENTS AND DOME OVERS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BUKLT DIKES AND PLACED BOOMS AROUND THE TRAILER AND AROUND THE STORM DRAIN IN THE CENTER OF THE INTERCHANGE. PRODUCT LOADED FROM THE TRAILER FOR ABOUT 2 OR 3 HOURS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED FORM TO CONTAIN THE VAPORS. THE NEXT DAY THE AREA WAS EXCAVATED AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVED.
column169: THIS ROLLOVER ACCIDENT WAS AS A RESULT OF HUMAN ERROR. THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING  AT A SPEED IN EXCESS OF WHAT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE TRUCK FROM ROLLING, LOADED AS IT WAS. PREVENTATIVE MEASURES WILL INCLUDE, BUT NOT BE LIMITED TO :  - PROGRESSIVE DISCIPLINARY ACTION TAKEN WITH THE DRIVER. - ADDITIONAL TARGETED REFRESHER TRAINING WITH ALL HANDS. - SUGGESTION: THERE WERE NO SPEED LIMIT SIGNS  POSTED, ON OR APPROACHING THE EXIT. THESE SIGNS ARE VERY IMPORTANT FOR TRUCKERS TO CALCULATE THEIR SPEED IN RELATION TO THE LOAD THEY  ARE CARRYING AND THE CONFIGULATION OF THEIR EQUIPMENT.. EVEN DURING CONSTRUCTION TEMPORARY SIGNS SHOULD BE POSTED. THESE SIGNS ARE ALSO VERY IMPORT TO THOSE INVOLVED IN THE ROAD CONSTRUCTION.

column168: AREA DISPOSAL TRUCK WAS STOPPED AT ILLINOIS STATE TRUCK SCALES, AT LITCHFIELD, IL, FOR BEING OVERWEIGHT ON THE DIRVE AXLES. THE DRIVER TRIED TO MOVE THE WEIGHT BUT COULD NOT. THE OFFICER AT THE SCALES TOLD THE DRIVE TO TRY TO RAISE THE BED ON THE DUMP TRAILER, TO SHIFT THE DUST TO THE BCK. THE DRIVER SAID THAT WOULD NOT BE A GOOD IDEA BECAUSE THE DUST FLOWS LIKE WATER BUT THE OFFICER SAID TO TRY IT AND SEE WHAT HAPPENS. THEY RAISED IT UP AND WENT BACK AND WEIGHED, STILL OVERWIEGHT. THE DRIVER OPENED THE TARP AND HAD ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER WATCH AS HE RAISED IT. A SMALL PILE MOVED AND THE DRIVER STARTED TO LOWER THE TRAILER AND THE LOAD BROKE LOOSE AND SPILLED OVER THE TAILGATE ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER SAID ABOUT A LOADER BUCKET, 2000 POUNDS, SPILLED ONTO THE GROUN BEHIND THE TRAILER, THE OFFICER AT THE SCALES SHUT THE SCALE DOWN TO KEEP TRAFFICE AWAY. BODINE ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THEIR REPORT IS ENCLOSED.

column168: A PART-TIME SORTER WHO WAS UNL9OADING A PACKAGE CAR NOTICED A GROUND SERVICES PACKAGE FROM BATTERIES PLUS WAS WARM TO THE TOUCH. HE NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT AND A TRAINED RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND RESPONDED. BY THE TIME THE RESPONDER APPROACHED THE PACKAGE. THERE WAS SOME SMOKE COMING OUT OF CREASES FROM UNDERNEATH THE TAPE. THE BOX WAS EXPANDING SLIGHTLY AS WELL. THE RESPONDER TOOK THE PACKAGE OUTSIDE SO IT WAS IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA. AFTER ROUGHLY 15 MINUTES THE BATERY STOPPED REACTING AND THE SMOKE AND MOST OF THE SMELL WENT AWAY. AFTER THE BATTERY REACTION CEASED. THE BATTERY CASE, WHICH WAS FOR USE IN A POWER DRILL OR SIMILAR TOOL. WAS WARPED AND MELTED. THE REACTION ALSO MELTED A SMALL PORTION OF THE BATTERY CHARGER THAT WAS IN THE PACKAGE AS WELL.
column169: INVESTIGATE CAUSE OF INTERNAL FAILURE.

column168: RICHEM WAS LOADING A TRUCK OWNED BY ARTIC EXPRESS GOING TO UTAH. THE LOAD WAS 43,142 LBS. THE CARRIER WAS CALLED AND ACCEPTED THE WEIGHT. THE DRIVER REQUESTED THAT THE LOADER LEAVE 4 SPACES IN THE NOSE TO HELP OFFSET THE WEIGHT OF THE REFER UNIT. THE LOADER PLACED DOUBLE STEAKS OF EMPTY PALLETS IN THE NOSE TO KEEP PALLETS & PRODUCT FROM SLIDING FORWARD. ONE LOAD LOCK WAS ALSO USED TO BRACE THE LOAD FROM MOVING AS WELL. PALLETS WERE ALSO STRETCHER WRAPPED AND BARDED. THE BALANCE OF THE TOTAL WAS PUT ON THE TRUCK AND A 2ND LOAD LOCK WAS PLACED AT THE END OF THE LAND. DRIVER SIGNAL A LEFT THE FACILITY AND RETURNED APPROX. 2 HOURS LATER. HE PULLED INTO THE DRIVEWAY WITH THE LOAD LEAKING. RINCHEM EMPLOYEES PLACED A POOL UNDER THE LOADING TRAILER AND PLUGGED THE CATCH BASIN WITH PIGS. SOAKS AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE DRIVER CLAIMED THAT HE WAS CUT OFF SO EH JACKED ON HIS BRAKES AND SWEAR TO AVOID THE CAR IN WHICH THE LOAD SHIFTED.
column169: ALL RINCHEM EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN RE-TRAINED IN OUR DOCUMENT SHIPPING & RECEIVING. ALONG WITH THE RETRAINING, ADDITIONAL RETRAINING RELATED TO THE FEDERAL MOTOR CARRIER SAFETY ADMIN. SUBPART J SECTION 393.100 393.102, 313.104 AND 393.9 HAVE ALSO BEEN COVERED. BASED ON THE SPECIFICS OF THIS INCIDENT, RINCHEM EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO USE NO LESS THAN 5 PALLET SPACES AS SPACES WHEN SPREADING OUT A LOAD ACROSS A TRAILER. THIS WAY THE 5 PALLETS SIT HIGHER THAN THE CENTER OF THE DRUM. WE BELIEVE THIS PRACTICE WILL PREVENT DRUMS OR ANY PUT OF THE LOAD TO SHIFT PAST THE SPACES. WITH CURRENT LOAD BARS. STRETCH WRAP & HANDING ALONG WITH EXTRA HIGH SPACES WE BELIEVE AFTER ANY EXTREME BRAKING OR SWERVING THIS WILL PREVENT ANY SHIFTING OR SLIDING.

column168: Our petroleum delivery truck was northbound on USTH 169 at mile marker 174 after pulling out from a delivery stop.Our driver got to approximately 45 MPH when he was hit from behind. Damage from the contact ruptured the delivery truck's two rear meters, piping and hoses. There is one each, gasoline and diesel meter and hose there.The product released approximately 20 gallons of gas and 20 gallons of diesel fuel was ignited by some source and burned off. It did not run off. The rear most tank compartment was not breached.A local fire department member witnessed the accident and called for an immediate Fire Department response. TheFD was there within 10 minutes and kept the truck tanks cool until the product present from the hoses, meters and piping burned away. This took approximately 40-50 minutes before the fire was out.Northbound traffic was re-routed to the southbound side of the road for approximately 1.5 hours while the gasoline  was pumped to another of our delivery trucks. Clean up was completed to the Highway Patrol's satisfaction by ourown employees.
column169: This incident would of been tough to avoid on our part. It's very difficult to predict getting hit from the back when the road is open ahead of you in clear summer weather. The driver hitting our truck was sited for inattentive driving, he just wasn't paying attention. I have talked to the driver involved here and all of our employees to always be alert to all that is happening around them and if possible react in a way to avoid contact.

column168: AR Trucking, Inc driver Craig O’Connor was loading a tanker with crude oil from a tank at the Howard Drilling location en Route 321 approximately 8 miles from Kane, PA when he became ill and lost consciousness. The result of his illness and lost consciousness was the result of food poisoning as the Warren General Hospital later showed upon evaluation of the driver. His loss of consciousness prevented him from shutting down the loading pump when the tanker was full. This resulted in an overflow of approximately 20 to 21 barrels of oil most of which was recovered as oil or by clean up. According to the Department of Environmental Protection, approximately 2 gallons of oil made it to the South Branch of the Kinzua Creek and the bulk of those 2 gallons were recovered as clean up. When the spill was discovered by our driver, he enlisted the aid of two Howard Drilling employees who helped damn up the oil on the ground and called AR Trucking, Inc immediately for help. Four employees went directly to the site and began cleanup with employees from the American Refining Group, Howard Drilling and C line Oil. The DEP commented that the immediate reaction saved more oil from hitting the waterway and we were all commended for the quick response and actions taken. Per the DEP’s suggestion, a professional cleanup company was hired by us to dictate the balance of the cleanup which was completed by mid July and included in my final report to the DEP and the Environmental Protection Agency, which has now considered the case closed. The duration of the release was most likely approximately two to five minutes. AR Trucking Inc is now installing See-Level Gauges with Spill Stop Switches in our tanker trucks, In the event a driver becomes incapacitated) the unit will shut down the pump when the tank becomes full preventing any overfill and any spill. This is a safety feature both for our drivers and the environment in which we work.
column169: We encourage our drivers to inform us of any and all Illnesses so that we can determine if they can safely perform their daily duties. The installation of the See-Level Gauges and Spill Stop Switches was our recommendation for prevention of any future spills.

column168: On June 23, 2008 a United Industrial Services (United) employee was extracting material from 300 gallon steel totesat AMRI-Rensselaer using a high capacity vacuum truck. While extracting material from a storage unit using a highvolume vacuum system the unit shut down prematurely causing a release of product. Typically a high volume unitsuch as this is utilized on high viscous/high gravity material. In this application the volume of air and fluid mixturecaused the product to foam in the vessel giving false readings to primary and secondary shutoffs causing a releaseof product from the venting system in conjunction with the vacuum pump. Approximately 10 gallons was released toan asphalt base which was immediately absorbed with absorbent material. With the unit shut down, product neededto be transferred back into the storage unit to allow for the reset of the primary and secondary shutoffs. Whileattempting to reload the storage unit from the vacuum vessel an overflow of product occurred in a containment areadue to the lack of gauging required to conduct the transfer in an orderly fashion. The resulting overflow releasedapproximately 80 gallons of liquid into containment.-
column169: All of the vacuum truck check systems were in place and functional which helped to ensure that a larger release didnot occur. Since the incident, United has set up routine communications with AMRI-Rensselaer so routine pickupsare scheduled and inventory is kept low. Future transfer of this type of material will not be performed with a highvolume vacuum system unless the vacuum tank unit volume is less then 70% of tank capacity. This will insure anyproduct foaming will not cause a premature shut down of the vacuum system. United has also made it a practice tosend the same trained personnel to this location. The personnel sent to this location are familiar with the operationsat this location and the types of materials to be handled. United Industrial Services feels these steps will help ensurethat future releases will not occur.

column168: On June 19, 2008, CPR staff observed liquid leaking from tank car GATX 7534. The container was transporting sulfuric acid. Wenck Associates, Inc. (Wenck) received a call from Mr. Dale Buckholtz of Canadian Pacific Railway (CPR) requesting emergency response assistance associated with the above-referenced container. Wenck dispatched an emergency response team to assist in the response activities. Once onsite Wenck had CPR personnel secure track protection in order to safely perform all necessary activities. The response crew donned personal protective equipment and assessed the situation. Upon investigation it was noted that the manway gasket had moved from the sealing surfaces of the manway hatch cover. The response crew opened the manway cover and replaced the gasket into the grooves. The manway cover was re-secured using a 24 inch pipe wrench. Exterior surfaces of the railcar were ph adjusted utilizing a Simple Green... and water mixture. Simple green is a non toxic biodegradable cleaner/surfactant. Tank car GATX 7534 originated in Trail, British Columbia Canada. Wenck contacted Teck Cominco metals, Ltd. (a.cethe shippera.) to notify them of the incident. Upon completion of the response activities Wenck spoke to Mr. Bill Minkler of Teck Cominco Metals, Ltd., the emergency contact listed on the shipping information to give him an update on the response and to inform him the tank car was cleared for transport to its destination.

column168: The shipper was traveling via PAX aircraft from the Hollywood, FL. airport. He was allegedly advised by TSA that the lighter could not travel on the PAX aircraft, but that it could be shipped via FedEx. The shipper put the lighter in a FedEx Pak ,filled out an international air waybill and dropped the lighter into a FedEx DropBox at the HWO Airport. When the package was brought to the FedEx station, we found that the shipment was a domestic move on the inappropriate air waybill. At that point the package was opened to reveal the lighter. There were no markings,labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The lighter, we believe is forbidden by air as it contains unabsorbed lighter fluid. The FAA was notified, I spoke to FAA SA Veronica Laughlin. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.
